pathway is unaffected, while vasoconstriction pathway is inhibited","Vasodilation pathway is inhibited, while vasoconstriction pathway is unaffected","Both vasodilation and vasoconstriction pathways are amplified","Vasodilation pathway is amplified, while vasoconstriction pathway is inhibited"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn obesity, insulin resistance primarily affects the vasodilation pathway. Insulin normally promotes vasodilation by stimulating the production of nitric oxide in endothelial cells. However, in the context of insulin resistance, this pathway is impaired, leading to reduced vasodilation. This contributes to hypertension and other cardiovascular complications associated with obesity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVasodilation pathway is inhibited, while vasoconstriction pathway is unaffected\u003C/strong\u003E is correct because the vasoconstriction pathway, which is mediated by endothelin-1, remains largely unaffected by insulin resistance. This imbalance between impaired vasodilation and preserved vasoconstriction can exacerbate vascular dysfunction in obese individuals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBoth vasodilation and vasoconstriction pathways are inhibited\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because the vasoconstriction pathway is not typically inhibited in obesity-related insulin resistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVasodilation pathway is unaffected, while vasoconstriction pathway is inhibited\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as it is the vasodilation pathway that is impaired, not the vasoconstriction pathway.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBoth vasodilation and vasoconstriction pathways are amplified\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because insulin resistance does not amplify these pathways; rather, it impairs vasodilation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVasodilation pathway is amplified, while vasoconstriction pathway is inhibited\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as insulin resistance leads to impaired vasodilation, not amplification.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In obesity, insulin resistance affects the pathways regulating vasodilation and vasoconstriction differently.","Insulin resistance in obesity leads to impaired vasodilation while vasoconstriction pathways remain unaffected."],"references":["Klein S, Gastaldelli A, Yki-J\u00e4rvinen H, Scherer PE. Why does obesity cause diabetes? Cell Metab. 2022 Jan 4;34(1):11-20. doi: 10.1016/j.cmet.2021.12.012. PMID: 34986330; PMCID: PMC8740746.","Hardy OT, Czech MP, Corvera S. What causes the insulin resistance underlying obesity? Curr Opin Endocrinol Diabetes Obes. 2012 Apr;19(2):81-7. doi: 10.1097/MED.0b013e3283514e13. PMID: 22327367; PMCID: PMC4038351.","Go\u0142acki J, Matuszek M, Matyjaszek-Matuszek B. Link between Insulin Resistance and Obesity-From Diagnosis to Treatment. Diagnostics (Basel). 2022 Jul 10;12(7):1681. doi: 10.3390/diagnostics12071681. PMID: 35885586; PMCID: PMC9321808.","Barazzoni R, Gortan Cappellari G, Ragni M, Nisoli E. Insulin resistance in obesity: an overview of fundamental alterations. Eat Weight Disord. 2018 Apr;23(2):149-157. doi: 10.1007/s40519-018-0481-6. Epub 2018 Feb 3. PMID: 29397563."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58360"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17929"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58360"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T13:07:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-22T13:07:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10643"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72890"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"descrip